    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Stands made to support hot water urns or teakettles. May be short-legged stands that are set upon a table, or taller stands with legs that reach the floor. For tables that support a tea service, use "tea tables." Use "teakettles-on-stands" for teakettles made en suite with a stand.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099620/Legacy AAT data</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079686/Montgomery, American furniture: Federal Period (1966)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Bases fabricadas para mantener urnas de agua caliente o teteras. Use "tetera sobre soporte” para teteras hechas a juego con un soporte.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
